<F P=100> RUSSIA INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Grachev Stresses Pan-European Security System </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD1001215094 Moscow Mayak Radio Network in Russian 1930 GMT 
10 Jan 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD1001215094 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow Mayak Radio Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Russian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] A two-day summit of NATO member-countries opened in 
Brussels today. It discussed as its central issue the 
Partnership for Peace plan proposed by U.S. President Bill 
Clinton. This envisages the establishment of military links 
between the North Atlantic Alliance and the countries of East 
Europe and the former Soviet republics, including the Russian 
Federation. 
  As is known, Russia does not object to these links, but is 
opposed to NATO's expansion into countries in close proximity to 
the Russian borders. Incidentally, experts of the Russian 
Defense Ministry note that NATO itself lacks unity of views 
regarding the next steps after the possible adoption of the U.S. 
Partnership for Peace plan. Army General Pavel Grachev, Russian 
defense minister, speaks about the stand of the Russian military 
in greater detail: 
  [begin Grachev recording] We are advocates of a path that 
leads to a truly pan-European system of security. This means 
collective actions -- but not in accordance with the criteria of 
membership in the bloc -- aimed at preventing and settling the 
crises and conflicts now shaking Europe. I believe that 
security and international stability should be indivisible and 
should be based on common European structures. Russia is 
proceeding from the fact that our relations with NATO should be 
richer and should develop in broad-ranging cooperation. We 
believe that rapprochement between Russia and NATO should be 
going at an accelerated pace. [end recording] 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

