<F P=100> RUSSIA INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Yeltsin Invites Ukraine's Kravchuk to Trilateral Summit </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD1001164594 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1613 GMT 10 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD1001164594 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [From the "Diplomatic Panorama" feature] </F>
  [Text] In view of the agreement reached in principle on 
some important bilateral issues, including those connected with 
nuclear arms, President Boris Yeltsin invited his Ukrainian 
counterpart, Leonid Kravchuk, to come to Moscow, the Russian 
president's press service said on Monday. 
  The communique says that a working 
Russian-American-Ukrainian 
top-level meeting will take place in the Kremlin on January 14. 
According to an understanding reached between Boris Yeltsin and 
Bill Clinton, the American president may make a brief stop in 
Kiev's airport, Borispol, on January 12 on his way to Moscow. 
  At 16:00 on January 10 U.S. diplomats in Moscow announced 
they knew nothing about any stopover at Kiev's Borispol Airport 
on his way to Moscow. Their message was received by Interfax. 

</TEXT>

