<F P=100> RUSSIA INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Kravchuk Visit `Would Be Problematic' </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD1001181994 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1136 GMT 10 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD1001181994 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Informed sources in the Russian Foreign Ministry 
told Interfax that Ukrainian President Leonid Kravchuk would 
arrive in Moscow to meet with Presidents Boris Yeltsin and Bill 
Clinton. The three presidents are expected to meet on January 
14. 
  The sources also said that the reports on Clinton's visit to 
Ukraine were "groundless." 
  Meanwhile, informed sources in Kiev told Interfax that the 
authorities there do not rule out the possibility of President 
Clinton's stopover in the Ukrainian capital. They say that a 
meeting of Kravchuk and Clinton could resolve all issues in the 
stationing of nuclear weapons in Ukraine that cause American 
concern. The same sources note that in this case Leonid 
Kravchuk's trip to Moscow would be "problematic" unless 
trilateral documents could be signed there. 

</TEXT>

