<F P=100> RUSSIA INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Troops in Put on Alert </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD1001190194 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 1848 GMT 10 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD1001190194 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Moscow January 10 TASS -- The Russian Defence 
Ministry issued the following statement on Monday, following the 
blockade of Russian military facilities by Latvian paramilitary 
units and detention of two Russian generals and the Russian 
ambassador's car. 
  "On the morning of January 10, 1994 armed groups of 
Zemessargs (Latvian paramilitary units) seized several 
facilities on the outskirts of Riga. Major-General Nikolay 
Taylakov, deputy commander of the Northwestern Group of Troops, 
and Major-General Anatoliy Vodopyanov, assistant to the 
commander of the Northwestern Group of Troops for work with 
personnel, arrived at the scene of the incident. In return to 
their demand to leave the seized facilities, the chairman of the 
Vidzeme district gave on order to arrest the generals. The 
Russian generals were handcuffed and put into a car which drove 
towards the Russian border. Commander of the Northwestern Group 
of Troops Colonel-General Leonid Mayorov informed the Russian 
defence minister about the incident. Defence Minister Army 
General Pavel Grachev issued an order to put Russian troops 
stationed in Latvia on alert and tighten security at the 
facilities and premises belonging to the Northwestern Group of 
Troops. On alert were also placed air-borne troops and military 
cargo aviation. The commander of the Northwestern Group of 
Troops informed Latvian President Guntis Ulmanis about the 
incident. The president expressed bewilderment over the 
incident, gave orders to free the detained generals and offered 
his apologies. By 17:00 the Russian generals and all seized 
facilities were freed. 
  The Ministry of Defence of the Russian Federation demands an 
immediate investigation and punishment of those guilty. Any 
violent or unlawful acts against the Russian servicemen, 
military units and facilities of the Russian Army will be 
checked in the most decisive manner. Responsibility for all 
possible consequences in this case will rest with the local 
authorities who must ensure a normal situation around the 
Russian military units," the statement said. 
  The generals were freed only after the intervention of the 
Russian Embassy. The Latvian authorities sent their apologies 
for the incident and assured the Russian Embassy that the 
facilities were being unlocked. 
  Early on Monday a group of Latvian militants stopped a car 
of 
the Russian ambassador and refused to let it pass despite the 
ambassador's protests. After long deliberations they allowed 
the car to pass but waived their guns at it. 
  The Russian Embassy issued a protest to the Latvian Foreign 
Ministry, describing the incident as a potentially dangerous 
provocation. The embassy expressed the hope that the Latvian 
authorities will take the necessary measures to prevent such 
incidents in the future. The note considered the incident as an 
attempt to thwart the talks on the troop withdrawal. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS3-55341 </DOCNO>
