<F P=101> Estonia </F>
<H3> <TI>   Government Policy Not To Change </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  WS0701113494 Tallinn BNS in English 0708 GMT 7 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> WS0701113494 </F>
<F P=104>  Tallinn BNS </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Tallinn, Jan 06, BNS - The policy of the Estonian 
Government won't change after the replacement of some of the 
ministers, Prime Minister Mart Laar said in an interview with 
BNS today. 
  Instead, it will provide the opportunity to more 
consistently 
carry out the current policy and change just a few points of 
emphasis, he said. 
  Laar said the government planned to pay special attention to 
the tax reform and to putting the Tax Department to work. Laar 
criticized the Finance Ministry, which in his words had delayed 
reforms and in some cases ever "worked against them." 
  He said the Economics Ministry under the new minister was 
expected to pay more attention to working out legislations. 
  Laar said he was sure that the ministerial changes were not 
going to bring down the professionalism of the Cabinet. "The new 
ministers have gained experience in politics, which will enable 
them to come to better terms with the parliament," he said. 
  The prime minister declined to comment on whether or not the 
other coalition partners -- the Moderates and the Estonian 
National Independence Party -- had plans to replace any of their 
ministers. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

