<F P=100> BALTIC STATES </F>
<F P=101> Estonia </F>
<H3> <TI>   Official Says Delineation of Border With Latvia Unnecessary </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  WS0601181694 Tallinn BNS in English 0959 GMT 6 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> WS0601181694 </F>
<F P=104>  Tallinn BNS </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Tallinn, Jan 06, BNS -- Estonian political circles 
seem to have reached the conclusion that a border between 
Estonia and Latvia is not needed, Udo Helme, the head of the 
Estonian delegation to the joint border commission, charged in 
an interview to BNS today. 
  "Since Estonia and Latvia have established a visa-free 
regime 
between the two countries, erroneous references to several 
western countries that also don't require entrance visas are 
made," Helme said. "People who do so confuse the different 
functions of a border -- the political, the juridical, and the 
security ones. 
  "This is detrimental to the de facto restoration of the 
Republic of Estonia as an independent state," Helme claimed. 
  A Foreign Ministry official told BNS that Vello Saatpalu, 
the 
chairman of the parliamentary Foreign Commission, made a 
proposal to the government to stop designating the boundary 
between Estonia and Latvia, since it is "a waste of the 
taxpayers' money." 
  Under the Estonian-Latvian agreement on restoring the 
boundary concluded in March 1992, Estonia is to mark off the 
border from the Pededze River in the east to the town of Valga, 
and Latvia, from Valga to Ikla in the west. 
  Estonia has until now marked off an 82-kilometer stretch of 
the border out of a total of 158 kilometers. 
  The cost of the work was originally estimated at 9.2 million 
kroons, of which 2.3 million has been spent. 
  A Foreign Ministry official, speaking on condition of 
anonymity, told BNS that, if the work is suspended, resuming it 
will cost Estonia an additional 4 million to 4.5 million kroons. 
Denmark's aid to the amount of 2.4 million Danish kroner will in 
this case also stop. 
  "Thus, it is most doubtful if stopping the construction 
saves 
the taxpayers' money," the official told BNS. 
  Under the agreement, the demarcation of the border should be 
completed by the end of 1995. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

