<F P=100> Lithuania </F>
<H3> <TI>   Premier Returns; Comments on Farmers Strike </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  WS0601200294 Vilnius ELTA NEWS BULLETIN in English 1755 GMT 
6 Jan 94 </F>

<F P=103> WS0601200294 </F>
<F P=104>  Vilnius ELTA NEWS BULLETIN </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [From ELTA "NEWS BULLETIN" No. 409] </F>
  [Text] Vilnius, Jan 6 (ELTA) -- Lithuanian Premier Adolfas 
Slezevicius gave his first news conference after his holidays in 
Florida on January 6. He commented on the state budget of 1994 
and expressed his satisfaction about the fact that a possibility 
had been found to finance restoration of historical buildings. 
Then Slezevicius returned to current problems. 
  At present one of the major problems is the forthcoming 
farmers' strike in February. Slezevicius said that he had met 
with the chairman of the strike committee Jonas Ciulevicius just 
before the news conference. At the meeting which lasted about 
an hour possibilities of avoiding the strike were discussed. 
  "The right to go on strike is guaranteed by the 
Constitution, 
but the organizers of the strike must know that they have no 
right to force farmers to go on strike and stop supplying 
processing enterprises with produce. The fact that strikers 
will take their produce to market places instead of processing 
enterprises shows that this action could hardly be called a 
strike as they had a similar right before", Slezevicius said. 
  Another important problem is the construction of the oil 
terminal. Slezevicius emphasized that the construction of the 
oil terminal in Liepaja did not mean that another terminal would 
not be built in Butinge. Slezevicius told the press once again 
that if the terminal is build in Liepaja, Lithuania should have 
the controlling block of shares, that is 51 percent of capital. 
In addition, Lithuania should get some land in the port 
territory for building the joint-venture as well as some land 
for construction of the oil pipeline to Mazeikiai. The final 
decision on the issue should be adopted next week in Liepaja at 
the meeting of Lithuanian and Latvian state delegations. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

