<F P=100> RUSSIA INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Foreign Ministry Spokesman Holds News Briefing </TI></H3>
<H4>   Lithuanian Statements on Kaliningrad `Unfriendly' </H4>
<F P=102> LD0601165094 Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service in Russian 1535 
GMT 6 Jan 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD0601165094 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Russian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS diplomatic correspondents Boris Krivoshey and </F>
Aleksandr Krylovich] 
  [Text] Moscow, 6 Jan (ITAR-TASS) -- Lithuania's unfriendly 
statements about Kaliningrad Oblast cause bewilderment and could 
complicate Lithuanian-Russian relations. This was said at a 
briefing today by Grigoriy Karasin, director of the department 
of information and the press of the Russian Foreign Ministry, in 
connection with the latest statements by some Lithuanian 
politicians who have called for the "demilitarization" and 
"deoccupation" of Kaliningrad Oblast, for a review of its 
international status, and for it to be removed from Russia by 
forming on its territory "a new Baltic republic integrated into 
the structures of Northern Europe." 
  In connection with this the Russian diplomat recalled that 
the decision of the Potsdam Conference on transferring 
Kaliningrad Oblast to the Soviet Union was final and without any 
time limit. The territorial possession of the oblast by the 
Soviet Union and consequently by Russia was subsequently laid 
down in the treaty on the final settlement in relation to 
Germany of 12 September 1990 and the treaty on 
good-neighborliness, partnership, and cooperation between the 
USSR and the FRG of 9 November 1990. "Thus, juridically and by 
right of morality and history Kaliningrad Oblast is an 
inalienable, integral part of Russia, and Russia will not permit 
a review of the international legal acts establishing and 
confirming its present status," he stressed. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

