<F P=100> RUSSIA INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Foreign Ministry Spokesman Holds News Briefing </TI></H3>
<H4>   Concerned by Nagorno-Karabakh Fighting </H4>
<F P=102> LD0601164194 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1427 GMT 6 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD0601164194 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Spokesman for the Russian Foreign Ministry Grigoriy 
Karasin has described the latest developments in the zone of the 
Azeri-Armenian conflict as more bloodshed and another attempt to 
settle the conflict by force. This is taking place in 
conditions when the world community, including Russia, proposed 
real possibilities for the bloodless solution of disputed 
problems by peaceful means, the spokesman told a briefing in 
Moscow January 6. 
  Karasin said that over the past two weeks the Azeri armed 
forces were fighting to liberate some of the republic's regions 
earlier captured by units of the Karabakh Armenians. There are 
widespread hostilities around Nagorno-Karabakh with heavy 
casualties. 
  The spokesman drew the attention of journalists to the two 
sides' mutual accusations of responsibility for the resumption 
of fighting, shelling and new offensives. This is not 
infrequently close to manipulating the public opinion and 
non-critically reproduced by the media causing misinformation, 
said the diplomat. He believes the propagandist war only 
aggravates the profound mutual mistrust between the conflicting 
sides. 
  The spokesman has voiced regret that Baku rejected the 
proposals of its Russian mediator put forward on December 16 and 
20 on a temporary cease-fire which would create more favorable 
conditions for signing an agreements on ending hostilities. 

</TEXT>

