<F P=100> RUSSIA INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Foreign Ministry Spokesman Holds News Briefing </TI></H3>
<H4>   Urges `Restraint' in Afghanistan </H4>
<F P=102> LD0601161094 Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service in Russian 1520 
GMT 6 Jan 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD0601161094 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Russian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS correspondent] </F>
  [Text] Moscow, 6 Jan -- Continuing to occupy a position of 
noninterference in the conflict inside Afghanistan, Russia calls 
on all sides involved to display restraint, to reject actions 
using force, and to seek political compromises for the sake of 
national consolidation. This was stated by Grigoriy Karasin, 
director of the information and press department of the Russian 
Foreign Ministry, at a briefing today. 
  He noted that Russia views with deep concern recent events 
in 
Afghanistan, the flaring up of armed clashes in Kabul and in the 
north of the country which have already caused numerous 
casualties, including among the civilian population. It is 
evident that such a development can only further intensify the 
polarization of the forces in Afghan society, make the prospects 
for restoring peace in Afghanistan even more remote, and 
seriously complicate the situation on the southern frontier of 
the CIS and in the region as whole, the Russian Federation 
Foreign Ministry spokesman stressed. 
  Together with other states and the United Nations, Russia is 
prepared to assist the process of achieving an Afghan 
settlement. Grigoriy Karasin said getting such a settlement 
going and furthering it would correspond to the common interests 
of the whole of the international community. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

