<F P=100> RUSSIA INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Foreign Ministry Spokesman Holds News Briefing </TI></H3>
<H4>   Views Proposals for CIS Development </H4>
<F P=102> LD0601180194 Moscow Mayak Radio Network in Russian 1430 GMT 
6 Jan 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD0601180194 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow Mayak Radio Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Russian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] At the Russian Federation Foreign Ministry press 
center today a briefing was held for Russian and foreign 
journalists. Speaking at it, Grigoriy Karasin, director of the 
Russian Foreign Ministry's Information and Press Department, 
said, among other things: 
  [Begin Karasin recording] About the plans of the Russian 
side 
as chairman of the Commonwealth of Independent States: In 
connection with the decision of the Ashgabat meeting of CIS 
heads of state, that the Russian Federation would, at the 
present stage, take the chair in the main bodies of the CIS, the 
Russian Federation Foreign Affairs Ministry is beginning to work 
out proposals for specific ways of the future development of the 
CIS. These proposals, that are based on results already 
achieved within the Commonwealth, cover the following main 
areas: Establishing the mechanisms for an economic alliance; 
ensuring human rights and the rights of minorities throughout 
the CIS, and creating mechanisms to guarantee these rights; 
restoring cultural, scientific, and educational ties between the 
Commonwealth countries; creating a unified humanitarian space; 
shaping an effective system of collective security, with the 
stress on peacekeeping functions; developing practical 
mechanisms of the CIS to prevent armed conflicts; ensuring 
greater effectiveness for joint action by members of the 
Commonwealth in the foreign-political sphere in the development 
of cooperation between the CIS, the United Nations, the CSCE, 
and other international organizations. 
  The corresponding ministries and departments will take part 
in drawing up these proposals. The Foreign Ministry also 
intends to draw in the representatives of scientific circles and 
public organizations. These proposals will be submitted to the 
Russian leadership, and then Russia, as the current chairman of 
the CIS, will table them for examination by the other 
Commonwealth member states. [end recording] 

</TEXT>

