<F P=100> RUSSIA INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Clinton, Aides Cited on Inadvisability of NATO Expansion </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PM0601132594 Moscow KRASNAYA ZVEZDA in Russian 6 Jan 94 p 3 </F>
<F P=103> PM0601132594 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow KRASNAYA ZVEZDA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Russian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [ITAR-TASS correspondent Pavel Vanichkin report: "`We </F>
Cannot Move the Berlin Wall to the East'"] 
  [Text] Washington, 5 Jan -- The preparation for the 
imminent 10-11 January conference of NATO heads of state and 
government and the prospects of expanding U.S.-West European 
trade and economic cooperation were the focus of attention 
during a conversation in the White House between U.S. President 
Bill Clinton and Netherlands Prime Minister Ruud Lubbers, who is 
here on an official visit. 
  Speaking to journalists before the meeting began, B. Clinton 
said that discussion of his proposed "Partnership for Peace" 
concept, which provides for the phased integration of East 
European countries in NATO, must be one of the main themes on 
the agenda at the upcoming Brussels conference of NATO 
countries' leaders. However, according to the U.S. President, it 
would be premature to start talking abut the possibility of 
giving Poland, Hungary, and the Czech Republic full membership 
status in NATO right now. 
  "I am not opposed to expanding NATO," the head of the White 
House stressed. However, from what he said "there is no accord" 
at the moment among the organization members as to the 
expediency of accepting East European countries. "Therefore, 
following many decades of work to abolish the `boundary' 
dividing Europe, we do not want to create the impression that we 
are aspiring to a new division of the continent," Clinton said. 
"We favor a secure and stable Europe. At the same time, I 
believe that sooner or later the `Partnership for Peace' concept 
will lead to an expansion of NATO." 
  When asked whether in his view the implementation of this 
concept would lead to the integration of all European states, 
including Russia, in the North Atlantic Alliance, the U.S. 
President said: "I hope that ultimately all European countries 
will clearly and unequivocally put themselves in the hands of a 
peaceful, stable, and secure Europe, whose states will respect 
each other's borders." 
  "We cannot simply move the Berlin Wall several hundred miles 
to the East," General John Shalikashvili, chairman of the U.S. 
Joint Chiefs of Staff, stated at a White House news conference 
Tuesday. He warned against "creating a division" in Europe 
again, whether "deliberately or unintentionally," and expressed 
his opposition to expanding NATO at present by including former 
Warsaw Pact states. 
  Speaking to journalists on the same day, U.S. presidential 
national security adviser Anthony Lake stressed that the United 
States is committed to the "evolutionary" process and is 
avoiding drawing "new demarcating lines" right now between East 
and West in Europe. The hasty acceptance of East European 
countries into NATO could lead to the destabilization of the 
region and "would be an involuntary confirmation of pessimistic 
predictions in respect of Russia," was the way he explained 
Washington's official viewpoint. This, in his opinion, would not 
be in line with "either NATO's interests or the interests of the 
states of Central and East Europe." Lake deemed it necessary to 
stress that this position enjoys the support of President Bill 
Clinton. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS3-55381 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drsov005_a_94008" </HT>


