<H3> <TI>   Deputy Foreign Minister Says U.S Talks `Very Successful' </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD0601173594 Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service in Russian 1548 
GMT 6 Jan 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD0601173594 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Russian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS diplomatic correspondent Georgiy Shmelev] </F>
  [Text] Moscow, 6 Jan -- The Russo-U.S. consultations held 
in the U.S. capital were very successful; an agreement was 
reached on all of the main points of the program for U.S. 
President Bill Clinton's state visit and of the agenda for the 
summit meeting in Moscow, Georgiy Mamedov, the Russian 
Federation deputy foreign minister, believes. He has just 
returned here from Washington, where he discussed the program 
for the visit with Strobe Talbott, coordinator of U.S. policy 
toward Russia and the CIS countries. 
  In Georgiy Mamedov's view, the Moscow forum will devote its 
main attention to problems of economic interaction between the 
countries, and examination of a set of questions linked with the 
implementation of the policy of reform in Russian society. On 
the international level, the sides will consider the 
strengthening of security and the settlement of regional 
conflicts, particularly in Bosnia and Nagorno-Karabakh, and also 
problems of nuclear nonproliferation and cooperation in arms 
control. 

</TEXT>

