<F P=100> RUSSIA NATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> Political &amp; Media Issues </F>
<H3> <TI>   Chernomyrdin, Shumeyko Begin Talks With Journalists </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD0601152194 Moscow Mayak Radio Network in Russian 1330 GMT 
6 Jan 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD0601152194 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow Mayak Radio Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Russian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] A meeting between Prime Minister Viktor 
Chernomyrdin, First Deputy Prime Minister Vladimir Shumeyko, and 
the editors in chief of Russian periodicals and the heads of 
newspaper unions has begun at the Russian Government House on 
Krasnpresnenskaya Naberezhnaya. This is the first meeting the 
head of the Russian cabinet has had with such a representative 
group of journalists since he became prime minister a year ago. 
  The meeting may untie the complex knot of problems which has 
risen since the government's 25 November decision to reassess 
the basic assets of national economy enterprises. Media chiefs 
believe that the increase in the value of the basic assets of 
printing enterprises will lead to a six-fold increase in the 
cost of typographical services. The critical situation which 
has emerged has thus far all but led, like all journalists' 
protests, to a suspension of the publication of a number of 
publications from 10 January. 
  Opening the meeting, Viktor Chernomyrdin stressed that the 
Russian Government is looking closely at the journalists' 
problems, but he expressed the opinion that the journalists, who 
from the outset have favored market reform, have today become 
fully integrated into market conditions. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

