<F P=100> Lithuania </F>
<H3> <TI>   Brazauskas on Joining NATO, Ties With Russia </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD0601205994 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1746 GMT 6 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD0601205994 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Lithuanian President Algirdas Brazauskas believes 
that Lithuania's decision to join NATO should not change the 
relations established with Russia and other neighboring states. 
  Brazauskas declared this to the Russian service of 
Lithuanian 
national radio, which he visited on Thursday together with Prime 
Minister Adolfas Slezevicius. 
  Brazauskas underlined that this political move should not be 
viewed as an intention "to change or to toughen relations with 
Russia and other states." In his words, leaders of all European 
countries should have reached an agreement on creation of "a 
single security umbrella." 
  Slezevicius added that "Lithuania's orientation towards the 
West does not represent any innovation in our foreign policy" 
and integration into the European security system, such as NATO, 
"would be a premise for stabilizing the situation in the 
region, and this is important both for Lithuania and all 
neighboring states." 

</TEXT>

