<F P=100> RUSSIA INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Foreign Ministry Spokesman Holds News Briefing </TI></H3>
<H4>   Questions Lithuania's `Haste' Over NATO </H4>
<F P=102> LD0601164594 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1427 GMT 6 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD0601164594 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] A Russian Foreign Ministry official believes that 
"the haste" with which Lithuania's President Algirdas Brazauskas 
has formally applied for NATO membership "looks odd and 
counterproductive." 
  Briefing newsmen in Moscow on Thursday, Foreign Ministry 
spokesman Grigoriy Karasin suggested that this step reflected 
the sentiments of "certain political forces which regard 
alignment with military and political unions as the key to 
national security." 
  He called "for giving more thought to what is of prime 
importance for guaranteed stability in Europe." 
  Moscow, in his words, favors "a genuinely European security 
system for all states, collective actions to meet any challenge 
today, and efforts to boost the CSCE potential." 
  "Equal security for each and everyone and cooperation rather 
than new dividing lines between states - that's what Europe 
requires today," Karasin declared. 
  In his words, such an approach prevails in CSCE, in the 
North 
Atlantic Cooperation Council, and in NATO itself. No wonder, 
the concept "Partnership for Peace" has been devised to 
strengthen security across Europe rather than within blocs. The 
concept has drawn much response. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

