<F P=100> UKRAINE </F>
<F P=101> International Affairs </F>
<H3> <TI>   Possibilities of Kravchuk-Clinton Meeting Viewed </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD1001105294 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 1017 GMT 10 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD1001105294 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS correspondent Yefim Shvartsman] </F>
  [Text] Odessa January 10 TASS - "We are studying now" the 
question of a place and time for a possible meeting between 
Ukrainian President Leonid Kravchuk and U.S. President Bill 
Clinton, Viktor Stelmakh, head of the press service of the 
Ukrainian president and the government said in a telephone 
interview with ITAR-TASS on Monday at 10:45, Moscow time [0745 
GMT]. 
  This is the only response by Ukraine for the time being to 
an 
issue which is of interest to many other capitals, apart from 
Kiev. 
  However, nobody doubts Ukraine's interest in such a meeting. 
Describing numerous possible versions, local analysts prefer 
three most probable: the first suggests that a meeting may take 
place at the Kiev Airport on January 12 if Clinton makes a 
stopover en route from Prague to Moscow. 
  According to the second version, the Ukrainian president 
will 
visit Moscow on January 14. The third presupposes the two 
presidents' meeting in Minsk on Sunday, January 16. 
  Kiev very painfully reacts to another inaccuracy circulated 
by various mass media, including Russian, concerning the number 
of missiles in Ukraine. Some periodicals wrote about 1,000 
nuclear missiles. 
  In actual fact, this is an error made as a result of 
confusing nuclear warheads with missiles. Ukraine has 176 
strategic nuclear missiles. Kiev believes that it is to destroy 
130 of them in compliance with the START-1 treaty. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

