<F P=100> UKRAINE </F>
<F P=101> International Affairs </F>
<H3> <TI>   U.S. Accused of Exerting Disarmament Pressure </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD0801184594 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1657 GMT 8 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD0801184594 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] The head of one of the commissions of the Ukrainian 
parliament has accused the United States of putting pressure on 
Ukraine to make it speed up its nuclear disarmament. 
  Dmytro Pavlychko, chairman of the parliamentary Commission 
on 
International Affairs, said such pressure, which came from 
Russia and the United States, could only give a better chance to 
radicals at the March 1994 parliamentary election. 
  "If we're talked to from a position of strength, the only 
result will be that we'll want to defend ourselves," he told 
reporters in Kiev. Ukraine is a sovereign state, "and we won't 
go on our knees before anyone, not even before the president of 
America," he said, commenting on a statement by a White House 
spokesman, who said on January 5 that U.S.-Ukrainian relations 
would remain at their present low level until Ukraine met all 
its nuclear disarmament commitments. 
  Pavlychko said the United States was mainly interested in 
Russia, with which Ukraine would, however, find "common 
language." "We have lived together and will continue to live 
together," he said. 

</TEXT>

