<F P=100> National Affairs </F>
<H3> <TI>   Reduced TV Broadcasting Schedules Resume </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD0701220794 Moscow Russian Television Network in Russian 
2000 GMT 7 Jan 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD0701220794 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow Russian Television Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Russian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [From the "Vesti" newscast] </F>
  [Text] The citizens of Ukraine have gotten used to 
surprises of all kinds from the government. In December they 
had time to resign themselves to the latest surprise, and not 
the most painful: under the new television broadcasting 
schedules, television channels have been working only from 1800 
until midnight on working days. 
  Broadcasting resumed in full in the New Year, but it turns 
out that viewers' rejoicing was premature. This was just a 
small Christmas present, and the restrictions come back into 
force on 10 January. Naturally the official reason remains the 
same: the shortage of electric power. However, local 
authorities in certain regions do not conceal their own view on 
the matter, using figures to prove how small the savings have 
been as a result of these restrictions and describing them as 
primarily a political move. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

