<F P=100> National Affairs </F>
<H3> <TI>   Banknotes Illegitimately Traded on Black Market </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD0701152794 Moscow Programma Radio Odin Network in Russian 
1200 GMT 7 Jan 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD0701152794 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow Programma Radio Odin Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Russian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] While reports of an impending currency reform which 
are sweeping the Ukraine are mere rumors at the moment, hryvnas 
are already being traded openly on the main market in 
Zaporozhye, the homeland of the Ukrainian Cossacks. Both 
bankers and law enforcement agencies are worried at this 
development. They want to know how the new banknotes, which 
were printed in Canada and, supposedly, kept securely under lock 
and key, turned up on Zaporozhye's black market. By all 
accounts, the black marketeers already know what the exchange 
rate for the new currency will be. 
  One hryvna is being exchanged for 24,000 karbovantsi, only 
50 
percent less than the U.S. dollar. 

</TEXT>

