<F P=100> Tajikistan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Conflicts Continue Along Afghan Border </TI></H3>
<H4>   `New Provocations' Reported </H4>
<F P=102> LD0701100694 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 0949 GMT 7 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD0701100694 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS correspondent Galina Gridneva] </F>
  [Text] Dushanbe January 7 TASS -- Tajik opposition 
fighters, based in Afghanistan, have staged new provocations on 
some sectors of the Tajik-Afghan border. 
  ITAR-TASS has learned today from military sources that a 
small gang of Tajik mojaheeds attempted on Thursday to break 
through the positions of Russian border guards, deployed on the 
Pyanj sector of the border, heading for Shartuz. However, they 
were stopped by Russian border guards and men from one of the 
battalions of the CIS peacekeeping force in Tajikistan and 
forced back into Afghanistan. 
  Futile also were the attempts of two small groups of Tajik 
opposition fighters to illegally cross into Tajikistan through 
the zone controlled by men of the 12th Russian border post. 
  According to the same source, Tajik mojaheeds, entrenched in 
several border provinces of the Islamic state of Afghanistan, 
have staged several more minor armed provocations since the 
beginning of January on sectors guarded by the Pyanj and 
Moskovskiy borderguard detachments. Two violators of the border 
were killed. There were no casualities among Russian servicemen. 

</TEXT>

