<F P=100> BALTIC STATES </F>
<F P=101> Estonia </F>
<H3> <TI>   Tallinn Reports Progress of Russian Withdrawal </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  WS0701212794 Tallinn BNS in English 1919 GMT 7 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> WS0701212794 </F>
<F P=104>  Tallinn BNS </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Tallinn, Jan 07, BNS -- The main Russian combat 
unit still stationed in Estonia, the 144th armored infantry 
division, keeps on taking its equipment out of Estonia, 
officials at the Estonian Defense Ministry say. 
  According to information obtained by BNS, the division 
headquarters applied to Estonian authorities for 80 different 
transport permits in December. The division took a total of 96 
vehicles and 1,800 tons of property out of the country on 16 
railway trains last month. 
  The division hired 8 trains to take 57 vehicles and 2,800 
tons of property out from Estonia in November. 
  As much as 254 vehicles and 5,300 tons of army property were 
taken out of Estonia by the same unit on 42 trains in July. 
  The division, stationed in bases in Tallinn, as well as at 
Keila and Klooga to the west of the capital, was still about 
1,000-strong in December. 
  The division's tank regiment, stationed in Keila, until now 
comes for shooting exercise to Manniku on the outskirts of 
Tallinn. The division's ammunition depots at Klooga and Manniku 
contained about 3,500 tons of ammunition at the end of 1993. 

</TEXT>

