<F P=100> Lithuania </F>
<H3> <TI>   Christopher Letter on `Evolutionary Expansion' Noted </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  WS0701175194 Tallinn BNS in English 1612 GMT 7 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> WS0701175194 </F>
<F P=104>  Tallinn BNS </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Vilnius, Jan 07, BNS -- U.S. Secretary of State 
Warren Christopher expects the upcoming NATO summit in Brussels 
to make decisions on the establishment of essentially new 
cooperation between the alliance and East European countries. 
  Lithuanian Foreign Minister Povilas Gylys received a letter 
from Christopher this week, saying the Brussels summit would be 
a favorable possibility to start closer security cooperation 
between the alliance and the newly emerging democracies in 
Eastern Europe, including Lithuania, the Lithuanian Foreign 
Ministry said. 
  Christopher said the summit is likely announce that NATO 
will 
welcome new members in the future. The alliance's evolutionary 
expansion would preserve its strength, harmony among its members 
and its ability to act. 
  The secretary of state said the Partnership for Peace 
program 
offers Lithuania close practical cooperation with both military 
and political structures of NATO. The initiative would require 
serious military and political steps -- to observe international 
obligations, to guarantee civil control of the armed forces and 
to properly arrange the military budget. 
  Christopher expressed hope that Lithuania will support the 
Partnership for Peace program and will take an active part in it. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS3-55458 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drsov006_v_94003" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-SOV-94-006 </AU>
Document Type:Daily Report 
<DATE1>  10 Jan 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> Lithuania </F>
<H3> <TI>   Gylys: NATO Request `Not Directed Against Anybody' </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  WS0701173894 Tallinn BNS in English 1612 GMT 7 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> WS0701173894 </F>
<F P=104>  Tallinn BNS </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Vilnius, Jan 07, BNS -- Estonia and Latvia were 
informed in advance about Lithuania's intentions to officially 
ask for NATO membership, said Lithuanian Foreign Minister 
Povilas Gylys. 
  In an interview with the leftist TIESA newspaper, Gylys said 
the reaction of the two Baltic neighbors was slightly different 
because Estonia is more reserved about Lithuania's step. 
Apparently, the Lithuanian minister gave the interview before 
Estonian President Lennart Meri's view on the matter was made 
public. 
  Gylys said "although we maintained close relations with 
NATO, 
our desire was unexpected to many." 
  The minister said Lithuania's request for NATO membership is 
based on national security interests and is not directed against 
anybody. "We move toward an era of politics without 
confrontation." 
  In Gylys opinion, rapprochement with the alliance is an 
evolutionary process, while Lithuania's move might only speed it 
up. "This depends not only on Lithuania." 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS3-55459 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drsov006_v_94004" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-SOV-94-006 </AU>
Document Type:Daily Report 
<DATE1>  10 Jan 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> Lithuania </F>
<H3> <TI>   Seimas Deputy Chairman on Foreign Policy </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD0701175994 Vilnius Radio Vilnius Network in Lithuanian 
1300 GMT 7 Jan 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD0701175994 </F>
<F P=104>  Vilnius Radio Vilnius Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Lithuanian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Excerpts] [Announcer] Today's news conference in the 
Seimas held by Seimas Deputy Chairman Aloyzas Sakalas focused 
its attention on foreign policy and international relations. 
[passage omitted] I asked him to describe our foreign policy 
  [Begin Sakalas recording] Lithuania's foreign policy must be 
based on some main principles. There must be a foreign policy 
concept containing some main principles. [passage omitted] 
Unfortunately, I do not at present see such a concept in our 
foreign policy based on principles. These principles should be 
as follows: Relations with the closest neighbors, relations with 
other countries. 
  In relations with the closest neighbors I would put in the 
first place relations with Russia. Russia, as is known, has 
taken over the rights of the former USSR, it has only taken over 
the rights of the former USSR. If only rights, then why not 
responsibilities, too? And if responsibilities, then such 
issues as compensation and others may be discussed. If it has 
taken over rights only, then on what basis? So much about 
relations with Russia. In addition, we must evaluate the 
Russian military doctrine that has been published and is well 
known. We must respond correspondingly to this doctrine. There 
has been no such response so far. [passage omitted] We must 
evaluate this doctrine. [passage omitted] We must support all 
democratic forces in Russia and evaluate statements by the 
Liberal Democratic Party. We have not done this so far. 
  When we have all such criteria, our evaluations, we will be 
able to conduct our diplomacy in relations with Russia. 
  As for other neighbors, for instance Poland, are concerned, 
we have no treaty with Poland, we have no treaty with Belarus. 
[passage omitted] We must evaluate on what basis we are prepared 
to sign a treaty with Belarus. [passage omitted] The trouble 
with Poland is the Zeligowski action and the Suwalki Treaty that 
was broken, and it seems to me that we must say whether we 
adhere or refuse [as heard], but there must be a decision, and 
not like it is now -- diplomats travel to Poland and back and 
there is no order. Either we firmly say that until this is 
evaluated we do not intend to sign the treaty, or give up some 
things and sign a treaty that does not mention history and deals 
with the present only. 
  As far as Germany is concerned, there are many people who 
have suffered from the Nazis, were deported to Germany and were 
lost there. The Bundestag is examining the issues of 
compensation and we should say something and not wait for 
something to happen. 
  And lastly, Latvia and Estonia. Either we integrate in a 
common economic zone with some common political obligations, or 
each country remains separately. We must think about this. 
[passage omitted] 
  We must not find ourselves under the influence of a single 
foreign state. [passage omitted] It must not happen that 60 
percent our economy is linked with some specific country that 
can later dictate its economic and political conditions. 
[passage omitted] 
  I do not think our statement on joining NATO will result in 
a 
positive decision. I think that there has to be an additional 
incentive for the West to think, as soon as possible, about the 
possibility of admitting us to NATO, but not yet as the solution 
of such possibility. [sentence as heard] [end recording] 

</TEXT>

