<F P=100> CAUCASUS </F>
<F P=101> Armenia </F>
<H3> <TI>   Offensive Launched Around Agdam </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  NC0901115894 Paris AFP in English 1107 GMT 9 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> NC0901115894 </F>
<F P=104>  Paris AFP </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Excerpt] Yerevan, Jan 9 (AFP)--The Azerbaijani Army 
launched a major two-pronged offensive in Nagorno-Karabakh on 
Sunday, as fighting continued around the Armenian-controlled 
town of Agdam, the enclave's separatist army headquarters said. 
  The Azerbaijani forces, backed by armoured vehicles, were 
heading toward Mardekert in northern Nagorno-Karabakh and toward 
Askeran in the east, some 30 kilometres (18 miles) from the 
capital Stepanakert, the army headquarters said. 
  Heavy fighting was also continuing around Agdam, a strategic 
Azerbaijani town two kilometres east of the Nagorno-Karabakh 
border, which was captured by Armenian separatists six months 
ago. 
  The Stepanakert headquarters confirmed that Goradiz, a key 
town near the Iranian-Azerbaijani border, had been recaptured by 
the Azerbaijani Army. 
  But it denied Baku's claim Saturday that Azerbaijan 
controlled the road linking Goradiz and Fizuli, on the southern 
border of Nagorno-Karabakh. 
  The Armenian separatists had "succeeded in halting the 
Azerbaijani offensive" in that area, the headquarters said. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

