<H3> <TI>   Shevardnadze, Minister Deny Russians in Tbilisi </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD0801193894 Moscow Russian Television Network in Russian 
1700 GMT 8 Jan 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD0801193894 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow Russian Television Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Russian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [From the "Vesti" newscast] </F>
  [Excerpts] For several days the Georgians have been 
preoccupied with two sensational news stories: first is the 
death of Gamsakhurdia, and the second, even more powerful, is 
that, according to rumors, 25,000 Russian troops have been 
brought into Georgia and are stationed in Tbilisi, near the 
Vaziani military airfield. To be honest, the people are more 
interested in Gamsakhurdia's suicide. [passage omitted] 
  As for the introduction of 25,000 Russian soldiers, the best 
informed person -- Georgia's Security Minister Igor Georgadze -- 
has given us an answer to this question: 
  [Georgadze] As for 25,000 Russian soldiers being stationed 
on 
Georgian territory, I can tell you with full responsibility that 
this does not correspond to reality. 
  [Correspondent] Georgia's Head of State Eduard Shevardnadze 
was simply shocked by this question. He said the following: 
  [Shevardnadze] Rumors are being circulated abroad that order 
is being poorly maintained in Tbilisi, and so why don't we call 
in the Russians and get them to organize a normal life for us? 
I think this is simply farcical. [Video shows correspondent 
reporting from Tbilisi, officials being interviewed] 

</TEXT>

