<F P=100> RUSSIA INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   U.S. Ties Moving Toward Technological Partnership </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD1001104194 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 1020 GMT 10 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD1001104194 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Moscow January 10 ITAR-TASS -- A new trend is 
emerging in relations between Russia and the United States: 
Transition has become from technological confrontation to 
technological partnership, according to Viktor Glukhikh, 
chairman of the State Committee for Defence Industries of the 
Russian Federation. 
  According to Glukhikh, one hundred joint projects in the 
field of basic and applied research, development, production and 
marketing are already being implemented. Recently a memorandum 
of mutual understanding was signed with the U.S. National 
Aeronautics and Space Administration which promises to become 
one of the major joint projects. It sets the parameters for 
joint basic research in aeronautics which will be implemented 
with the help of the potential, technical capacities and 
intellectual resources of both Russia and the United States. 
  We developed and produced arms separately but are now 
looking 
for sensible and ecologically clean methods of eliminating them, 
Glukhikh stressed. 
  Moreover, we have thrown open the doors of "closed" 
factories 
and research institutes to demonstrate our readiness to 
cooperate in the technological fields in which Russia's priority 
is beyond doubt. It is not accidental therefore that recognised 
American industrial leaders such as the Boeing, Pratt and 
Whitney, Hughes and Rockwell international corporations are 
among our present partners. 
  We have already passed over to the American side packages of 
proposals relating to conversion and involving enterprises in 
practically all defence industries. We would like to hope that 
the upcoming visit of President Bill Clinton to Russia will 
further boost Russian-American contacts in the field of research 
and industrial cooperation, Viktor Glukhikh said. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

