<F P=100> RUSSIA INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Ground Forces Commander Ends Visit to India </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD0801101094 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 0827 GMT 8 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD0801101094 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS correspondent Alexey Kuznetsov] </F>
  [Text] New Delhi January 8 TASS -- "Russia and India have 
favourable prospects of developing bilateral cooperation, 
including in the military sphere," commander-in-chief of the 
Russian ground forces Colonel General Vladimir Semyonov said, 
ending his official visit to India as head of a military 
delegation. 
  According to Semyonov, Russia is committed to developing 
friendly relations with India, regarding it not only as a 
"strong ally, but also as a guarantor of stability in the 
Asia-Pacific region." He said that one of the objectives of the 
visit was to analyse right there, in India, matters dealing with 
military-technical cooperation, which are of interest for both 
sides. We should work for removing doubts that emerged recently 
in the minds of our Indian partners, Semyonov said. 
  During the visit Semyonov held talks with senior officials 
of 
the Indian Defence Ministry and met commanders of all the three 
armed services. They discussed issues connected with the 
organisation in the republic of a production base for the 
modernisation of Russian tanks other other military hardware, 
with which the Indian Army is equipped, as well as its repair 
and operation. 
  The commander of the Russian ground troops visited the 
southern military district, the training centre of the armoured 
troops and the higher artillery school near Puna, the state of 
Maharashtra. Besides, he acquainted himself with the everyday 
life of the Indian Army and praised its combat preparedness, 
professionalism and the skill of its generals, officers and 
soldiers. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

