<F P=100> RUSSIA INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Deputy Foreign Minister on Protecting Citizens' Rights </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD0901172894 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 1647 GMT 9 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD0901172894 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Moscow January 9 TASS -- The Russian Foreign 
Ministry has worked out a special programme to protect the 
rights of Russians living in other countries, Deputy Foreign 
Minister Sergey Lavrov said. 
  Speaking on Russian television on Sunday, Lavrov said that 
the programme will be submitted to the government as soon as the 
sources of its financing are found. 
  He voiced concern about the position of many Russians in 
some 
republics of the former Soviet Union, especially in Latvia and 
Estonia where about 1.5 million Russians are deprived of their 
civil and political rights. 
  He said similar problems face Russians in Central Asian 
republics, including Kazakhstan. Although Russia has friendly 
relations with that republic, the Kazakh Constitution says that 
the Kazakh nation, rather that Kazakhstan's people, will seek to 
restore its statehood. This lends an ethnic flavour to the 
entire concept of statehood of Kazakhstan where Russians and 
Kazakhs account for about 40 per cent of the total each, the 
deputy minister noted. 
  Lavrov said that the idea of dual citizenship is 
encountering 
tremendous difficulties in former Soviet republics. He 
admitted, however, that although dual citizenship will not solve 
all the problems, it may have a positive psychological impact on 
people and help ease tension. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

