<F P=100> RUSSIA NATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> Political Issues </F>
<H3> <TI>   New Intelligence Service Chiefs Hold News Conference </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD1001123794 Moscow Russian Television Network in Russian 
1100 GMT 10 Jan 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD1001123794 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow Russian Television Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Russian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [By correspondent A. Dubnov; from the "Vesti" newscast] </F>
  [Text] Representatives of the newly reconstituted Federal 
Counterintelligence Service held a news conference today at the 
Foreign Ministry's press center in Moscow. On 5 January 1994, 
an edict of the Russian president endorsed the service's 
standing orders which, according to its deputy director Sergey 
Stepashin, was an expected surprise [as heard] for its members. 
  The new structure is not a copy of the disbanded Security 
Ministry but makes the service answerable directly to the 
president, as is the practice in many other countries. Its 
remit covers such important matters as identification, advance 
warning, and prevention of subversive and intelligence 
activities directed against the Russian Federation by foreign 
special services and organizations; supply of intelligence 
information on threats to Russia; the fight against terrorism, 
illegal trading in weapons and narcotic substances, and illegal 
armed groups; and also counterintelligence support to ensure the 
security of Russian borders. This is despite the fact that the 
border troops have reorganized into a separate federal service 
with ministry status. 
  One thing worth pointing out is that the Federal 
Counterintelligence Service's manpower has been cut by 46 
percent and will total 75,000 persons. The number of 
administrators has been more than halved. 
  In the new structure, the main emphasis is on strengthening 
the counterintelligence and the anti-terrorism departments. 
  So, this notorious power structure has undergone yet another 
overhaul. Time will show how effective this one will be. 

</TEXT>

