<F P=100> RUSSIA NATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> Political Issues </F>
<H3> <TI>   Kostikov Warns Communists Against New Attacks </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD1001155194 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 1456 GMT 10 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD1001155194 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS correspondents Anna Melnikova and Gennadiy </F>
Talalayev] 
  [Text] Moscow January 10 TASS -- On the eve of the first 
parliament session presidential spokesman Vyacheslav Kostikov 
warned communists against launching attacks on the president and 
the Constitution and added that the president wants to 
constructively work with the legislature. 
  Kostikov told a briefing on Monday [10 January] that there 
are signs that communists are planning to launch attacks on the 
president and the new Constitution in parliament thus resuming 
what the former anti-Yeltsin legislature had failed to complete. 
  "Unfortunately, according to information which we possess, 
there are big fears that some factions, in particular the 
communists, are getting ready for attacks on the government, the 
president. We have all grounds to expect that attacks on the 
new Constitution will be launched", he said. 
  Kostikov called on communist leaders to remember "the bloody 
trace left by communists and learn lessons from it" while 
criticising the young Russian democracy and accusing the 
president of dictatorship. 
  "On the eve of the first session of the State Duma I would 
like to recall the tragic events connected with the bolshevik 
history", he said referring, in particular, to the 
anti-Bolshevik uprising in the fortress of Kronstadt in 1921 
which was drowned in blood. 
  On Monday the Russian president decreed to rehabilitate the 
soldiers and navymen who were executed during and after the 
anti-Bolshevik uprising. 
  Kostikov said the president wants that cooperation with Duma 
goes calmly and constructively. "Tomorrow a new page of the 
Russian democracy begins and we are all interested that this 
stage of cooperation of the president, the government with the 
legislature is quiet and constructive", he stressed adding that 
the executive authority would "keep a close eye on the 
behaviour" of all parliamentary groups. 

</TEXT>

