<F P=100> RUSSIA NATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> Political Issues </F>
<H3> <TI>   Zyuganov on Russia's Choice Rejecting Talks on Duma Speaker </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD0701175894 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1625 GMT 7 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD0701175894 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] In his interview with Interfax on Friday [7 
January] Gennadiy Zyuganov, chairman of the Central Executive 
Committee of Russia's Communist Party, declared that the 
unwillingness of the bloc Russia's Choice to participate in the 
negotiations on the speaker of the State Duma, as declared the 
bloc's leader Yegor Gaydar, does not mean that the ongoing 
consultations would be concluded. 
  In his opinion, representatives of the Russia's Choice bloc 
"cannot come to ourselves" after the large defeat at the 
December 12 elections. Zyuganov believes that Russia's Choice 
does not understand that its influence in the parliament, in 
contrast to executive power bodies, is not a dominating one and 
it "will have to take into account" other political forces as 
well. 
  In Zyuganov's words, in the course of the negotiations the 
Communist Party will defend interests of all factions, including 
the Russia's Choice. Zyuganov called a compromise variant which 
was considered at the negotiations, namely when representatives 
of each of eight factions will head one key parliamentary 
committee (there are correspondingly eight committees). 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

