<F P=100> RUSSIA NATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> Political Issues </F>
<H3> <TI>   `Ready To Cooperate With All' </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD1001125894 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 1232 GMT 10 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD1001125894 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS correspondent Lyudmila Aleksandrova] </F>
  [Text] Moscow January 10 TASS -- The parliamentary group of 
the Liberal Democratic Party of Russia held its first meeting on 
Monday [10 January]. 
  Journalists displayed great interest in this event, since 
all 
other top party functionaries, apart from LDPR leader Vladimir 
Zhirinovskiy, as well as newly elected legislators are, in 
fact, unknown to the public at large. 
  However, despite Zhirinovskiy's assurances of his commitment 
to "openness and freedom of speech", journalists were barred 
from the business part of the meeting. They could only listen 
to a 30-minute speech by the party leader. 
  Zhirinovskiy said that the parliamentary group will consist 
of 64 legislators, 59 of whom were elected on the party list and 
five from one-seat constituencies. According to the LDPR 
leader, the group consists of representatives from "all 
professions, trades and social sections". 
  "The party's position is reconciliation," he said. "The LDPR 
is ready to cooperate with all but will not join blocs or 
agreements with anybody." According to Zhirinovskiy, there are 
"many good lawmakers" among communists and agrarian deputies, 
but they are beset with "negative historic past". 
  As for democratic blocs, Zhirinovskiy said that "there are 
people who treat us well". 
  Although the LDPR supports the new constitution in every 
way, 
regarding it "good for 90 per cent", the party plans to strive 
for creating "a strong parliament along with the strong 
president", the LDPR leader noted. 
  Zhirinovskiy underlined that the LDPR group will lend 
strength to parliament. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

