<F P=100> RUSSIA NATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> Political Issues </F>
<H3> <TI>   Liberal Democrats' Tactics in Duma Viewed </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD1001154294 Moscow Mayak Radio Network in Russian 1444 GMT 
10 Jan 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD1001154294 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow Mayak Radio Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Russian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Today, on the eve of the opening of the Russian 
parliament, we have more than once turned to the vital issue of 
tactics to be pursued by various factions in their work. You 
will now learn what tactics the Liberal Democratic Party of 
Russia [LDPR] faction is going to pursue in the State Duma. 
Their tactics are described for Mayak by Stanislav Zhebrovskiy, 
a member of the LDPR Supreme Council, the party's deputy 
chairman and a deputy in the State Duma. The recording was made 
on the telephone. 
  [Begin Zhebrovskiy recording] The Liberal Democratic Party 
will operate as a separate faction in the State Duma. This is 
because entering into blocs with someone always means colluding 
against someone else. The Liberal Democratic Party is going to 
the Duma not to wage war against someone, but to work in the 
interests of the state. That is, we stand for doing something 
in the interests of the state every day, and for agreeing to 
compromises. 
  We shall always be a constructive political force. We are in 
opposition to the present government, but, I repeat, it is 
constructive opposition. Our stand is: Whoever proposes a 
sensible law directed at safeguarding Russia's interests, we 
shall always back this law. This is what we mean when we say we 
are constructive. [end recording] 

</TEXT>

