<F P=101> Political Issues </F>
<H3> <TI>   `Russian All-People's Union' Holds Conference </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD0801134994 Moscow Russian Television Network in Russian 
1100 GMT 8 Jan 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD0801134994 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow Russian Television Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Russian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [By correspondent A. Dubnov; from the "Vesti" newscast] </F>
  [Text] Today at the eastern district prefecture building in 
Moscow, a working conference of the leaders of the Russian 
All-People's Union [RANU] took place. 
  The conference began with a wave of displeasure in the hall 
when the chairwoman attempted to address those in attendance as 
gentlemen. However, this vexing slip of the tongue did not 
affect the course of the meeting. On the agenda were economic 
and political issues as well as the RANU's tasks for the next 
six months. 
  The greater part of a speech by Nikolay Pavlov, one of the 
RANU leaders, was devoted to criticizing the president and the 
government. On the whole, it contained nothing new: the 
accusation that Yeltsin and the government had organized the 
putsch, the dissolution of parliament, the slump in 
manufacturing, corruption and criticism of foreign policy, and 
of the START II treaty in particular. It was asked why so many 
people had perished on October 3-4 if the balance of forces in 
the new parliament will not, in the opinion of RANU members, be 
in favor of those now in power, in so far as former deputies and 
opposition members have once again got into the Duma. [sentence 
as heard] 
  There was, however, recognition that the RANU is an 
insufficiently powerful political force and therefore it has 
been decided to re-register the movement as a party. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

