<F P=101> Political Issues </F>
<H3> <TI>   Centrist Bloc Discusses Early Presidential Elections </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD1001141394 Moscow Russian Television Network in Russian 
1100 GMT 10 Jan 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD1001141394 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow Russian Television Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Russian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [By correspondent T. Orlova; from the "Vesti" newscast] </F>
  [Text] Today in Moscow, representatives of centrist parties 
discussed the possibility of holding presidential elections in 
Russia this year. 
  Taking part in today's open sitting of the Centrist bloc, 
apart from the hosts, were representatives of 14 parties and 
associations whose political inclinations and ideologies were in 
complete contrast, even at first glance. For instance, the 
Sakharov Union of Democratic Forces -- the initiator and creator 
of the Centrist bloc; the Muzyka publishing house; and arriving 
slightly late, but accompanied by a whole detachment, leader of 
the Pamyat National Patriotic Front Dmitriy Vasilyev. Very 
impressive, don't you think? 
  It was Mr. Vasilyev who began the discussion on the only 
issue on today's agenda: The possibility of holding early 
presidential elections on 12 June this year. 
  Well, the sitting started very sluggishly, and after 
numerous 
appeals by Chairman Vladimir Voronin [head of Sakharov Union of 
Democratic Forces] to begin discussing this vital political 
question, which received no response, the distraught chairman 
had to repeat his opening speech once again to rouse the sleepy 
participants. 
  Today's meeting is expected to result in the signing of a 
joint document on the need for early presidential elections. 
Many participants already believe that such a decision will be 
adopted. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

