<F P=100> RUSSIA NATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> Political Issues </F>
<H3> <TI>   Prepartions for First State Duma Session Continue </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD0801154094 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 1435 GMT 8 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD0801154094 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Moscow January 8 TASS -- Ad hoc committees and 
parliamentary groups set up to handle the preparation of the 
first session of the State Duma, the lower house of Russia's new 
parliament, continued their work on Saturday. 
  Most heated debates took place at a meeting of the 
inter-regional association of independent deputies which was 
also attended by deputies who represent some Russian constituent 
republics and autonomous entities. The speakers stressed that 
independent deputies elected in individual constituencies who 
are not bound by any pledges to political parties, blocs and 
movements and who realise their responsibility before their 
voters, the constitution and Russia believe that "integration 
and coordination of efforts are necessary for real work of the 
State Duma." 
  The participants in the meeting discussed ways to reach the 
goals set by their joint declaration adopted on January 5. In 
the declaration they expressed their determination to build 
their activities in the State Duma on the basis of 
"parliamentary freedom and responsibility, common sense, 
political realism, pragmatism, and respect for opinions and 
positions of other factions and groups." They plan to nominate 
their own candidate to the post of the chairman of the State 
Duma as their first step in this direction. 
  The deputies called on their colleagues elected in 
individual 
constituencies to join their efforts for the benefit of all 
peoples of Russia. 
  The commission for the procedural regulations of the State 
Duma and the deputy status discussed key questions the solution 
of which should ensure the effective work of the parliament. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

