<F P=100> RUSSIA NATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> Political Issues </F>
<H3> <TI>   Yeltsin To Open Parliament </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD0801143194 Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service in Russian 1310 
GMT 8 Jan 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD0801143194 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Russian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS correspondent Anna Melnikova] </F>
  [Excerpts] Moscow, 8 Jan -- The opening of the Russian 
parliament, the Federal Assembly, which is scheduled to take 
place in three days, may be called the final result of the 
election marathon of last November and December. 
  The first sessions of the chambers will be held on 11 
January. They will sit separately because the Constitution does 
not provide for a ceremony of a joint opening session of the two 
parliamentary chambers. The chambers may sit together to hear 
messages from the president and the Constitutional Court and 
speeches of the leaders of foreign states, as well as on the 
occasions when the president of the country takes the oath of 
allegiance. [passage omitted] 
  In accordance with the Constitution of the Russian 
Federation, the Russian president is to open the first session 
of the upper chamber of the parliament. 
  The ITAR-TASS correspondent has learned from well-informed 
sources in the Kremlin that there are no plans for a "big 
opening speech" by the president in connection with the 
beginning of the parliament's work. It will most probably be 
just a message to the elected deputies, wishing them success. 
  According to the same source, Boris Yeltsin is planning a 
long program speech at a joint session of the two parliamentary 
chambers a little later, shortly after the Federal Assembly 
begins its work. It has been revealed that economic, political 
and social aspects of reform in Russia will be touched upon in 
that speech. At the moment it is still unknown in what form the 
president is going to convey it to the deputies; that is, 
whether it will be a message or whether he will deliver the 
speech in person. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

