<H3> <TI>   Shumeyko Meeting Prepares Agenda </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD1001154994 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1443 GMT 10 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD1001154994 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] The first session of the Federation Council, the 
upper house of the new Russian parliament, will open at 10:00 on 
Tuesday [11 January]. It will be held in the former Russian 
Press House, Ul. Pushkinskaya 26, and is to be addressed by 
President Boris Yeltsin, a source in the office of First Deputy 
Prime Minister Vladimir Shumeyko told Interfax. 
  A meeting chaired by Shumeyko on Monday prepared the agenda 
for the Federation Council's first day, which includes the 
election of the speaker, his deputies, chairpersons for 10 
proposed committees and the senior bodies of the house, as well 
as voting on session regulations. 
  Shumeyko is going to run for speaker, the source in his 
office said. 
  Federation Council deputies, who asked not to be identified, 
told Interfax that, in addition to Shumeiko and former chairman 
of the Moscow City Council Nikolay Gonchar, candidates to the 
post of speaker might include the chairmen of the parliaments of 
the Russian republics of Karelia and Komi, Viktor Stepanov and 
Yuriy Spiridonov. The deputies described the latter two as 
"independent politicians standing for a single Russian 
Federation." 
  The deputies said a motion was expected to be made to elect 
three deputy speakers, one representing the republics, one the 
regions, and one the autonomous areas of Russia. 

</TEXT>

