<F P=100> RUSSIA NATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> Political Issues </F>
<H3> <TI>   Registration of Deputies for Upper Chamber Viewed </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD1001150494 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 1353 GMT 10 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD1001150494 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Moscow January 10 ITAR-TASS -- Today, on the eve of 
the first sitting of the Federation Council, the upper chamber 
of the new Russian parliament, registration began of its 
deputies arriving in Moscow. 
  Delegates to the chamber from all component parts of the 
Federation were elected in two-mandate constituencies formed in 
all republics, except Chechnya, and every territory, region, and 
autonomy. 
  The list of the chamber's members comprise 171 deputies. 
According to the Russian Constitution, there total number must 
be 178, but no representatives were elected in Tatarstan and the 
Chelyabinsk region, where a repeat election is now scheduled. 
Only one deputy was elected in the Yamalo-Nenets Autonomous 
District. 
  The overwhelming majority of the chamber's members say they 
are office workers (152). A considerable part of them are 
officials of regional legislative and executive bodies of power. 
Eight deputies are entrepreneurs, three are peasants, one is a 
serviceman, and seven are unemployed, a spokesman for the 
information department told ITAR-TASS. 
  All of the deputies, except two, have graduated from 
institutions of higher learning. They include ten professors, 
and 19 doctors of sciences (twelve in economics, five in 
technical sciences and two in philosophy). Only two deputies 
are under 30 years of age, and seven are older than 65. 

</TEXT>

