<F P=100> RUSSIA NATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> Political Issues </F>
<H3> <TI>   Officials Back Science Ministry Policy, Criticize Academy </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD0901130294 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 1220 GMT 9 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD0901130294 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS correspondent Veronika Romanova] </F>
  [Text] Moscow January 9 TASS -- Directors of nine leading R 
&amp; D institutions of Russia have addressed President Yeltsin 
with 
a letter backing the policy of the Russian Ministry of Science, 
which gives priority to a competitory way of financing national 
research and development, in lieu of the centralized and 
"departmental" way of financing, suggested by Russia's Academy 
of Sciences. 
  Among the address' authors were directors of Kurchatov's 
Institute of Nuclear Physics, Institute of Physics of Russia's 
Academy of Sciences, Institute of Physical Chemistry, Russian 
Research Centre of Applied Chemistry and the All-Russian 
Research Institute of Electric Machinery. 
  The letter was written in response to a resolution adopted 
in 
December 1993 by the presidium of the Russian Academy of 
Sciences. The resolution said that the modern crisis of "the 
eldest scientific organization of the country" was largely 
caused by the lack of budgetary funds "passing through the 
Ministry of Science." 
  The presidium of the academy urged to reshuffle the Ministry 
of Science to the corresponding state committee which would 
focus solely on federal R &amp; D programs, and not on 
independent R 
&amp; D projects. In other case, the academy leaders warned they 
would submit a resolution of no confidence to Science Minister 
Boris Saltykov. 
  However, scientists who addressed Yeltsin wrote that such a 
policy would even further aggravate the collapse of science in 
Russia protesting against "the departmental principle of money 
distribution" as it "will result in equal empoverishment (of all 
institutions)." On the contrary, it would be better to keep 
pursuing the ministerial policy aimed at financing priority 
studies, they concluded. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

