<H3> <TI>   Defense Minister on Discipline in Armed Forces </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD0701222694 Moscow Radio Moscow in Russian to Tajikistan 
1700 GMT 7 Jan 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD0701222694 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow Radio Moscow </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Russian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [From the "Radio Slavyanka" program of the Russian Defense </F>
Ministry] 
  [Excerpts] You are listening to Slavyanka, the radio 
station of Russia's Ministry of Defense, and now -- and what 
could be more natural -- here is Russia's Defense Minister, Army 
General Pavel Grachev. The recording was made at the very end 
of the outgoing year when he was rounding up its results, and 
these results, I must say, were extensive and varied, and out of 
all that variety, we have selected the things that concern 
everyone directly: housing, conditions of service -- but each of 
you can add to the list yourself. Listen on. [passage omitted] 
  [Begin Grachev recording] [passage omitted] Regarding 
military discipline: the results of 1993 show that, 
unfortunately, due to serious failings in the work of staff 
commanders and educational organs at all levels, and also 
through lack of personal discipline, people continue to die, 
weapons, ammunition, and military property are misappropriated, 
and cases of absence without leave continue to occur. 
  The Ministry of Defense is making every effort to solve 
these 
problems. To illustrate this, we managed this year to slightly 
reduce the gravity of problems linked to losses and 
misappropriations of weapons and ammunition. In comparison with 
the identical period last year, the quantity of misappropriated 
weapons fell by a factor of more than 17. In comparison with 
1992, the number of dead was almost halved. 
  An order of the Ministry of Defense on measures for 
maintaining law and order and military discipline in the Russian 
Armed Forces has been worked out and dispatched to the troops 
with the aim of improving discipline in the forces. 
  We believe that its execution will enable the state of 
affairs in this area to be improved significantly in 1994. [end 
recording] 

</TEXT>

