<F P=100> RUSSIA NATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> Space Issues </F>
<H3> <TI>   `Mir' Crew Starts Preparations for Handover, Return </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PM0501161794 Moscow ROSSIYSKAYA GAZETA in Russian 5 Jan 94 
First Edition p 8 </F>

<F P=103> PM0501161794 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ROSSIYSKAYA GAZETA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Russian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Unattributed report: "Space Watch Continues"] </F>
  [Text] Vasiliy Tsybliyev's and Aleksandr Serebrov's space 
watch aboard the "Mir" orbital complex is continuing. 
  Over the last two days the scientific part of the crew's 
flight program mainly comprised geophysical studies. The 
cosmonauts took several series of shots of the earth's surface 
and carried out an experiment to assess the state of the 
atmosphere's ozone layer over various regions of our planet. 
Preparations have begun to hand over to the crew of the 15th 
main expedition, scheduled for liftoff 8 January. The flight of 
the "Mir" manned complex is going normally. The cosmonauts are 
healthy and feel fine. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS3-55574 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drsov006_b_94053" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-SOV-94-006 </AU>
Document Type:Daily Report 
<DATE1>  10 Jan 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> RUSSIA NATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> Space Issues </F>
<H3> <TI>   Space Crew Prepares To Launch 8 Jan </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD0601234294 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 1823 GMT 6 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD0601234294 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS correspondents Anna Bakina and Veronika </F>
Romanenkova] 
  [Text] Moscow January 6 TASS -- For the first time in the 
history of Russian cosmonautics a space crew will miss one 
back-up astronaut when it blasts off on January 8 for a 
rendezvous with the orbiting stations Mir. 
  The state commission has removed German Arzamazov from the 
stand- by crew in which he was included as a medical researcher, 
following his statement opposing the candidature of Valeriy 
Polyakov as a member of the main crew. Arzamazov vowed that 
Polyakov had not practiced medicine for a long time and 
therefore cannot fly as a medical researcher. He offered his 
own candidature. 
  However, Vasiliy Agapov, Russian deputy health minister, 
believes that Polyakov is a highly skilled professional who has 
been working as a deputy director of the institute of medical 
and biological problems for a long time. Additionally, he has 
spent 241 days in space. 
  During the flight, Polyakov will carry out medical 
experiments on himself. As for Arzamazov, he has developed some 
"psychological problems" in relations with his colleagues. 
Besides, he has never been in space before, Agapov said. 
  The deputy minister said that taking account Arzamazov's 
experience -- he has been in the cosmonauts's team for 17 years 
and been included in stand-by crews twice, -- he may be included 
as a crew member for the future Russian-American joint space 
flight. 
  Agapov stressed that according to the standing rules, the 
entire crew has to be replaced if one of its members is removed. 
However, in this particular case, because of the extraordinary 
nature of the situation, a "reserve cosmonaut" has been prepared 
for a flight "in case of emergency." 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS3-55575 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drsov006_b_94054" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-SOV-94-006 </AU>
Document Type:Daily Report 
<DATE1>  10 Jan 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> RUSSIA NATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> Space Issues </F>
<H3> <TI>   Crew Stands By </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD0701125094 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 0814 GMT 7 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD0701125094 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS correspondents Veronika Romanenkova and Semen </F>
Ivanov] 
  [Text] Moscow January 7 TASS -- Twenty-four hours are left 
before the start of the 15th main space expedition to the "Mir" 
orbital station. It is scheduled for 13.05 minutes 32 seconds 
Moscow time, January 8. 
  A "Soyuz TM-18" vehicle with three cosmonauts on board is to 
be orbited by Russian military-space forces from the Baykonur 
cosmodrome. The rocket is already in position on the launching 
pad. A meeting of the state commission is to endorse the main 
and stand- by crews today. 
  At present, the main crew includes Viktor Afanasyev 
(commander of the vehicle), Yuriy Usachev (board engineer), and 
Valeriy Polyakov (research cosmonaut, physician). The stand-by 
crew includes Yuriy Malenchenko (commander) and Tolgat 
Musabayev (kazakh board engineer). The docking of the "Soyuz 
TM-18" vehicles with the "Mir" orbital complex is to take place 
at 14 hours 50 minutes Moscow time on January 10 (plus-minus 10 
minutes). 
  The members of the 15th main expedition will work on board 
the station for three days together with the crew of the 14th 
main expedition -- Vasiliy Tsybliyev and Aleksandr Serebrov, who 
began their orbital flight on July 1st, 1993. Tsybliyev and 
Serebrov had to remain on orbit for 146 days (until November 24, 
1993), but due to difficulties with the timely delivery of 
carrier-rockets for the "Mir" complex, the crew's stay on the 
orbit was prolonged for 200 days (until January 17, 1994). The 
cosmonauts agreed to this prolongation. And now the landing 
capsule of the "Soyuz TM-17" transport vehicle is expected to 
touch down at 11 hours 25 minutes Moscow time, January 14. 
  Tsybliyev and Serebrov have made five exits into open space 
in the course of the flight, remaining there for a total of 14 
hours 2 minutes. The implementation of the planned research 
programme and experiments was impeded by the limited financing 
of technological, biotechnological, geophysical and applied 
studies. Therefore, priority attention had to be given to 
research carried out on the commercial basis (for instance, 
nature studies and ecological research carried out to German and 
American orders), to astrophysical experiments ordered by the 
space research institute of the Russian Academy of Sciences, and 
also to works needed to draw up a target programme for the 
"Mir-2" station. 
  The 15th main expedition is to stay on the orbit for 179 
days 
(up to july 4). But the research cosmonaut (physician) will 
remain on the orbit for a much longer period -- 427 days. He 
will play host to two more expeditions on board the "Mir" 
station this year, first to the 16th expedition which is to last 
for 135 days (from June 22 to November 2), and to the 17th 
expedition, which is to last 157 days (from October 3). The 
17th main expedition will include a representative from the 
European Space Agency. 
  The experiments that are to be carried out during the 15th 
main expedition will focus on medical research. No exits into 
the open space are planned. Supplies to the "Mir" station will 
be brought by three cargo "Progress M" transport vehicles. 

</TEXT>

