<F P=100> RUSSIA NATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> Space Issues </F>
<H3> <TI>   `Soyuz' Docks With `Mir' Complex </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD1001123994 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 1231 GMT 10 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD1001123994 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS correspondent Veronika Romanenkova] </F>
  [Text] Moscow January 10 TASS -- The Soyuz TM-18 spacecraft 
docked with the Mir orbital complex at 14.50, Moscow time, 
today, as was planned, ITAR-TASS learned at the press centre of 
the Russian military-space troops. The Soyuz TM-18 spacecraft 
brought to the complex the crew of the 15th main expedition, 
made up of Viktor Afanasyev (mission commander), Yuriy Usachev 
(flight engineer) and Valeriy Polyakov (cosmonaut researcher and 
physician). The docking was carried out under the guidance of 
Colonel General Vladimir Ivanov, commander of the military-space 
troops and chairman of the interstate commission for ensuring 
flights and exploitation of the Mir orbital complex. 
  Two crews will work jointly at the Mir complex for three 
days. They will conduct a number of biotechnological 
experiments, whose results will be taken to the Earth by Vasiliy 
Tsibliyev and Aleksandr serebrov (the 14th main expedition). 
They are expected to return on board the Soyuz TM-17 spacecraft 
at 11.25, Moscow time, on January 14. 
  Afanasyev, Usachev and Polyakov will spend 179 [as received] 
at the Mir orbital complex. They will conduct numerous medical, 
technical and astrophysical expediments and research. Polyakov, 
a physician, will remain at the orbital complex after his 
work-mates return to the Earth. His flight will last 429 days. 
He will work together with the crews of the 16th and 17th main 
expeditions (the crew of the latter will include a 
representative of the European Space Agency). 

</TEXT>

