<F P=100> RUSSIA NATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> Space Issues </F>
<H3> <TI>   Lack of Funds Delays Construction of 2d `Mir' Station </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD0801224694 Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service in Russian 1444 
GMT 8 Jan 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD0801224694 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Russian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS correspondent Veronika Romanenkova] </F>
  [Excerpts] Moscow, 8 Jan--The Russians have once again 
amazed everyone by their precision: the launching of the 
spacecraft "Soyuz TM-18"--planned for 13 hours 05 minutes 32 
seconds--was carried out with only a two-second delay, whereas 
the permissible divergence from the launch time is plus-minus 60 
seconds. [passage omitted] 
  Meanwhile, the Russian cosmonauts and their colleagues from 
other countries will have to work on the Russian "Mir" station. 
It is true that the shortage of funds has had its effect on the 
state of the orbital complex. Launched in 1986, the station was 
meant to exist in orbit for five years. The shortage of funds, 
however, has lead to the fact that setting up a substitute--the 
"Mir-2" station-- has been delayed. Regular work is being 
carried out on "Mir" to prolong its "life". 
  The "old age" of the station is already having a negative 
effect. It was noted at one of the latest sessions of the 
interstate committee that 661 defects have been revealed, 
including 18 during the period of the 14th main expedition (from 
1 July 1993). However, these defects do not pose any direct 
threat to the safety of the crew. [passage omitted] 

</TEXT>

