<F P=100> INTERREGIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Premiers of Central Asian States Meet in Nukus </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD1001132194 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1136 GMT 10 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD1001132194 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] A working meeting of the prime ministers of five 
Central Asian countries started in the Uzbek town of Nukus 
Monday [10 January]. 
  The presidents of Uzbekistan, Kazakhstan, Kyrgyzstan, 
Turkmenistan, and Tajikistan are expected to hold a meeting 
there on January 11. This meeting will continue the work 
started in Kyzyl-Orda last March when the leaders of the five 
countries agreed on joint action to rescue the Aral Sea and help 
the coastal areas. 
  The coordination committee of the Central Asian countries 
has 
drafted numerous documents for this meeting, notably guidelines 
on the interstate council and its executive committee and a 
concept of ways to revive the Aral Sea. 
  Informed sources close to the Uzbek government told Interfax 
that the leaders of the Central Asian republics would discuss 
numerous economic problems in introduction of national 
currencies when they meet in Nukus. Cooperation in the 
ecological or any other sphere is impossible unless these 
problems are resolved, the sources believe. 

</TEXT>

