<F P=100> Regional Affairs </F>
<H3> <TI>   `Joint Defense System' Agreed With Chechnya </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD0901164694 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 1625 GMT 9 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD0901164694 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Groznyy January 9 TASS -- Russia and the Chechen 
Republic agreed on Sunday to have a joint defence system. A 
draft agreement to this effect was signed by the Russian and 
Chechen Defence Ministries, the CHECHENPRESS news agency said. 
  Colonel Musa Merzhuyev, Chechen President Dzhokhar Dudayev's 
representative in the republic's Armed Forces main staff, said 
that under the agreement Russia will provide the Chechen Army 
with arms, equipment and ammunition, ensure their servicing and 
maintenance at its plants and train officers. It has also 
pledged not to use its Armed Forces against the Chechen Republic. 
  In turn, the Chechen Republic will participate in the joint 
defence system to repel possible aggressions and provide its air 
bases to Russian Air Force units in wartime. Additionally, it 
will take part in joint military manoeuvres and war games and 
will not join any military alliances or blocs aimed against 
Russia. 
  The draft agreement also stipulates that in peacetime the 
Chechen Republic will have an army not bigger than 1.5 per cent 
of its population. 

</TEXT>

