<F P=100> Latvia </F>
<H3> <TI>   Pavlovskis: Partnership for Peace `Not Concrete' </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  WS0701212494 Tallinn BNS in English 1919 GMT 7 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> WS0701212494 </F>
<F P=104>  Tallinn BNS </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Riga, Jan 07, BNS -- The U.S.-proposed program for 
the cooperation of the East European states with the NATO "is 
not as concrete and clearly cut as this document should be," 
Latvian Defense Minister Valdis Pavlovskis told BNS. 
  In the Pavlovskis words, the program should provide clearer 
conditions and terms for the entrance of the states, signatories 
to the program, into the NATO. 
  Danish Defense Minister Hans Haekkerup, who visited Riga 
earlier this week, already pledged Pavlovskis to do everything 
he could to amend the program, Pavlovskis said. 
  "My personal opinion is that Lithuania's application for the 
NATO membership was premature," Pavlovskis said. It prompted 
Russia to air its (negative) stance on the acceptance of the 
Central European countries to this organization with a pretext 
that the move could undermine the European security, the 
minister said. 
  Pavlovskis prognosticated that Western politicians would 
heed 
to Russia's anxiety in fear of the destabilization of the 
situation in Russia itself. 
  Subsequently, the Western leaders may refuse to amend the 
Partnership for Peace, said Pavlovskis. He also said he hoped 
his prognosis would not come true. 
  The East European security problems could be tackled much 
easier if "Europe guaranteed our security." Then, Eastern Europe 
could focus its efforts on the development of economy and 
democracy. Besides, the entrance to the NATO is very costly 
because the member states need good armament and equipment. 
  It would also be more advantageous for the NATO to grant the 
East European countries some security guarantees than to enroll 
new members. The motion would even benefit Russia by 
stabilizing the situation in its neighboring states. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

