<F P=100> Latvia </F>
<H3> <TI>   CSCE Official Visits on Minority Issues </TI></H3>
<H4>   Further on Human Rights </H4>
<F P=102> LD0701174994 Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service in Russian 1111 
GMT 7 Jan 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD0701174994 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Russian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS correspondent Galina Kuchina] </F>
  [Text] Riga, 7 Jan -- Max van der Stoel, CSCE high 
commissioner for national minorities, who has been studying the 
problems of citizenship in Latvia, ends his regular visit to 
this country today. 
  During his meetings he has been acquainted with the draft 
law 
on citizenship, which has already passed its first reading. The 
draft envisages that, depending on the demographic and economic 
situation, the [Latvian] Government will decide how many people 
are granted citizenship every year. 
  In the opinion of the CSCE commissioner, prospects for many 
citizens will remain vague. He suggests that one should be 
guided by the number of years people have lived in Latvia. 
  However, according to Saeima Chairman Anatolijs Gorbunovs, 
this approach will lead to a "large wave of naturalization." 
The parliament head said a repatriation program is needed, 
which would encourage people to leave voluntarily. In his 
opinion, the CSCE structures could demonstrate initiative by 
drawing up such a program. 
  During his visit Max van der Stoel was told that non-Latvian 
citizens intend setting up an association to protect the 
interests of more than 700,000 people. Representatives of the 
initiative group handed him a list of laws which restrict the 
rights of citizens with no citizenship, who amount to one-third 
of the population. They are deprived of the opportunity to work 
as lawyers and judges, to own land, to freely choose their place 
of residence in Latvia, and to go to some European countries 
without a visa. The bill on the elections to local authorities, 
which has passed two readings, does not allow them to elect and 
be elected. Sergejs Dimanis, leader of the "Equality" 
[Ravnopraviye] movement, commented on the bill in detail. 
  The Latvian Foreign Ministry press service reports that at 
the meeting with the head of the Foreign Political Department, 
the CSCE commissioner said he "can see no violations of human 
rights in Latvia." 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS3-55604 </DOCNO>
