<F P=100> Latvia </F>
<H3> <TI>   140 Russian Families Send Letter to Clinton </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD0801155394 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1415 GMT 8 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD0801155394 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] 140 Russian families, belonging to the resettling 
association "Roots" and wishing to return to Russia for 
permanent residence, have sent a letter to President Bill 
Clinton. 
  They note that attempts to secure credits from the 
governments of Latvia and Russia to build settlements in the 
Pskov region where construction sites have already been provided 
for repatriates have been deadlocked. 
  They tell Clinton that they would appreciate assistance from 
American businessmen to build a construction materials 
enterprise, a creamery and a meat packing plant in the area. 
  "We do not want to be a blind weapon in the hands of 
nationalists like Zhirinovskiy and his party, playing skillfully 
on our feelings," the message says. 
  As the Association's Chairman Vyacheslav Tikhomirov has 
reported to INTERFAX, about 5000 people are ready to leave 
Latvia for Russia. 
  According to the results of a poll made available earlier in 
the week to Max van der Stoel, the CSCE high commissionaire for 
ethnic minorities who visited Latvia last week, 160,000 people 
want to go to Russia and 190,000 to western countries from 
Latvia. 

</TEXT>

