<H3> <TI>   Shushkevich Expresses Views on Clinton's Visit </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  WS1101121294 Minsk ZVYAZDA in Belarusian 6 Jan 94 p 1 </F>
<F P=103> WS1101121294 </F>
<F P=104>  Minsk ZVYAZDA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Belarusian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by Valer Kalinowski: "Shushkevich on Clinton's Visit </F>
to Belarus] 
  [Text] [Supreme Soviet Chairman] Stanislav Shushkevich has 
described the upcoming 16 January official visit by U.S. 
President Bill Clinton as an important and positive event for 
Belarus. Currently, special committees are preparing and 
drafting special interstate agreements. Stanislav Shushkevich 
emphasized that an array of important agreements is to be signed 
during the visit. In his opinion, the main goal of the visit is 
to clarify positions on the main strategic objectives of our 
policy and, in particular, the issue of Belarus' security. We 
would like to obtain guarantees for the protection of our 
neutrality -- such as Finland once received from the United 
States and the USSR -- when Belarus implements its 
constitutional law on neutrality and nonnuclear status, stressed 
Stanislav Shushkevich. Additionally, the Belarusian Supreme 
Soviet chairman noted that he does not expect that such a 
statement can be voiced by the United States already on 16 
January, however certain steps will undoubtedly be made. 
  Commenting on Bill Clinton's "Partnership for Peace" 
initiative, Stanislav Shushkevich stated that he considers it 
expedient to examine Belarus' official strategy in establishing 
in Central Europe a belt of neutral states with certain 
guarantees from great states of the world. 
  Additionally, Stanislav Shushkevich believes that Bill 
Clinton's visit to Minsk will contribute to Belarus' 
international image and encourage U.S. investment in its economy. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

