<H3> <TI>   Opposition Denounces Shushkevich, Opposes NATO Entry </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  WS1001155394 Minsk RID in Russian 1025 GMT 10 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> WS1001155394 </F>
<F P=104>  Minsk RID </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Russian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Representatives of the opposition Belarusian 
Popular Front [BNF], Z. Paznyak, V. Golubev, and S. Naumchik 
have held a news conference at the Belarusian Supreme Soviet. 
In the words of S. Naumchik, "despite the resistance of certain 
circles," U.S. President Clinton will visit Kuropaty [burial 
site of thousands of victims murdered by Soviet security police 
in the 1930's] on 16 January and meet with BNF Chairman Z. 
Paznyak. "The initiative to meet came from the American side," 
Z. Paznyak specified. The parliamentary opposition leader also 
voiced harsh criticism of Belarusian Supreme Soviet Chairman 
Shushkevich for signing the CIS Collective Security Treaty. He 
accused Shushkevich of betraying the national interests of 
Belarus. Speaking on the issue of unifying the Belarusian and 
Russian monetary systems, Z. Paznyak noted that Russia is 
"waging economic war against Belarus," and that the last 
agreement concluded by Yeltsin, Kebich, and Chernomyrdin means 
that "our country has surrendered." At the news conference, 
parliamentary opposition activists denounced Belarus' entry into 
NATO. "Only a policy of neutrality and the support of European 
states will help Belarus survive," Z. Paznyak emphasized. In 
addition, he said he doubted that the elections set for this 
spring will actually take place. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

