<F P=100> WESTERN REGION </F>
<F P=101> Belarus </F>
<H3> <TI>   Discrepancies With Russia on Monetary Union Reported </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  WS1001152794 Minsk BELAPAN in Belarusian 1156 GMT 10 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> WS1001152794 </F>
<F P=104>  Minsk BELAPAN </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Belarusian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] As BELAPAN has learned at the National Bank of 
Belarus [NBB], there are two principal discrepancies between 
Belarus and the Russian Federation as to the unification of 
monetary systems of the two countries. The first one concerns 
currency exchange rates. Belarus insists that NBB's bills be 
exchanged for Russian rubles at the one to one rate. Russia 
demands that the rate be one Russian ruble to three Belarusian 
ones. Another controversy is that whereas Belarus demands that 
Russia's internal prices for energy sources be extended to 
Belarus, representatives of the Russian Government do not agree 
with this. The Russian Ministries of Finance and Economy 
present a particularly uncompromising position. Yet another 
meeting of Russian and Belarusian Government delegations is to 
be held in January, at which attempts to solve the problems are 
to be made. The visit last week to Moscow by a Belarusian 
delegation resulted, as is known, in signing another declaration 
on intentions to unify the monetary-credit systems of Belarus 
and Russia. 

</TEXT>

