<F P=100> Moldova </F>
<H3> <TI>   Snegur Rebuts `Irresponsible Accusations' </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PM1001125994 Moscow ROSSIYSKAYA GAZETA in Russian 10 Jan 94 
p 6 </F>

<F P=103> PM1001125994 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ROSSIYSKAYA GAZETA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Russian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Lyudmila Feliksova report: "Moldova: President's Protest"] </F>
  [Text] Chisinau -- The election struggle in Moldova is 
gathering momentum. The usual methods are being employed to see 
who can inflict the worst bite. An official spokesman for the 
Moldovan president has issued a statement on the election 
campaign, in the course of which M. Snegur's is being bandied 
about in a variety of contexts and for a variety of reasons. 
Opposition political forces are accusing him, in particular, of 
not failing to give international publicity to the conflict in 
the Dniester region and of bringing about economic disaster in 
the republic. The president rejected all these charges as 
absurd and unsubstantiated. Snegur promised to issue a 
statement in the very near future "in response to irresponsible 
accusations by those who have turned patriotism into a trade" 
and to name those who are really to blame for the bloody 
conflict on the Dniester. Snegur once again peremptorily 
brushed aside suspicion of being involved in affairs connected 
with a branch of the Seabeco firm, which is headed by his 
son-in-law. Finally, he expressed confidence that the people 
will make their choice and thereby dot all the "i's." 

</TEXT>

