<F P=100> INTERREGIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   CIS Border Troop Commanders Meet in Ashgabat </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD1001145194 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 1421 GMT 10 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD1001145194 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS correspondent Lyudmila Glazovskaya] </F>
  [Text] Ashgabat January 10 TASS -- The Council of Border 
Troop Commanders of the Commonwealth of Independent States 
opened its meeting in Ashgabat, the capital of the Turkmen 
Republic, on Monday [10 Janaury]. The commanders will discuss 
illegal migration and drug trafficking across outside borders of 
the commonwealth states. 
  They will also examine principles of cooperation in logistic 
supplies to border troops. The meeting will last two days. 
  Turkmen president Saparmurat Niyazov received the commanders 
on Monday morning. At the reception, the Turkmen president 
pointed to the importance of political factors which, emerging 
under the influence of new processes, affect positively 
relations between neighbouring states. 
  He instanced relations between Turkmenistan, on the one 
hand, 
Russia and Iran, on the other, which, "thanks to mutual respect 
and trust, opened a possibility to find ways for settling all 
problems, including border issues". 
  Niyazov singled out the factor of inviolability of the 
present borders as a guarantee of peace and quietude, stressing 
that his recent talks with Iranian President Rafsanjani 
"revealed full concurrence of the two leaders' views on these 
and other issues of cooperation". 
  "While touring the world, we saw that there were no borders 
with barbed wire anywhere. They remain only as a heritage of 
the former Soviet Union," Niyazov noted. He expressed hope in 
this connection that the present Ashgabat meeting and the 
following ones will bring closer the solution of problems 
existing on CIS borders. 

</TEXT>

