<F P=100> INTERREGIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   ITAR-TASS Carries Press Review for 11 Jan </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD1101073394 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 0613 GMT 11 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD1101073394 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> ["Press Review" -- ITAR-TASS headline] </F>
  [Text] Moscow January 11 TASS -- Russian newspapers 
highlight a major event of the day -- the opening of a session 
of the newly elected parliament of the country -- the Federal 
Assembly. 
  NEZAVISIMAYA GAZETA, while noting that for 11 days Russia 
has 
had no parliament at all, points out that by the beginning of 
the session the deputies' factions in the State Duma have failed 
to reach agreement on important questions, despite numerous 
talkfests. 
  "As far as the Federation Council session, opening here on 
Tuesday, is concerned, one can suppose that a struggle for 
leading positions in it will be no less tough than that in the 
Duma." 
  TRUD on the Federal Assembly functioning: 
  "The legal life of the Federal Assembly begins today. Will 
it be marked by an end to antagonism between branches of power 
and by businesslike contacts between the parliament and the 
government? It is only businesslike contacts that can bring 
reassurance and future material wellbeing to the country". 
  PRAVDA on the first State Duma session: 
  "The first day of the session of the State Duma will be 
decisive... Despite a certain played-up excitement, the general 
impression is that the deputies want and are prepared to work 
efficiently". 
  NEZAVISIMAYA GAZETA carries an interview with Yuriy Baturin 
who was recently appointed the first assistant to the president 
of Russia on national security affairs. 
  Having pointed out that there are a lot of difficult tasks 
in 
this field, Baturin emphasised that "Russia's national security 
existed before and is still being elaborated". His opinion is 
that the concept "should be continuously modified in response to 
changing conditions. In our days, conditions change fast". 
  TRUD runs an interview with Sergey Stepashin, first deputy 
director of Russia's Federal Counterintelligence Service (FCS) 
which was founded by a presidential decree. 
  Stepashin dwelt on how the newly-established service differs 
from the old one and singled out six main tasks of the FCIS, the 
first among them being "to expose, prevent and put a stop to 
intelligence and subversive activities of foreign secret 
services and organisations against Russia". 
  PRAVDA carries notes by Former Russian Parliament Speaker 
Ruslan Khasbulatov. The notes, dated October 3, last year, are 
headlined "Notes from the `White House'". Khasbulatov analyses 
the situation in Russia after the August of 1991, expresses 
considerations about "direct motives for the anti-state coup" 
(as Khasbulatov describes the presidential decision to terminate 
the functioning of the Supreme Soviet and Congress of People's 
Deputies -- note by ITAR- TASS), and criticises President Boris 
Yeltsin's policy, the kingpin of which, as Khasbulatov 
maintains, is "antagonism and confrontation" 
  NEZAVISIMAYA GAZETA carries an interview with Ramiz Rizayev, 
Azerbaijan's plenipotentiary representative in Russia, who 
denied information that Afghan mojahedin take part in combat 
operations on Azerbaijan's side in the Armenian-Azerbaijani 
conflict over Nagorno-Karabakh. 
  In SOVETSKAYA ROSSIYA, Vladimir Isakov, former people's 
deputy of Russia and one of the leaders of the National 
Salvation Front, strongly criticises the current privatisation 
policy. He believes that "everything seems to indicate that 
privatisation in Russia will go down in history as an example of 
unprecedented and shocking social hypocrisy". 
  PRAVDA on President Clinton's forthcoming visit to Moscow: 
  "The U.S. delegation again has in its bag more pieces of 
advice and political declarations than specific economic 
programs, and, most importantly, funds for their realisation". 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

