<AU>   FBIS-SOV-94-007 </AU>
Document Type:Daily Report 
<DATE1>  11 Jan 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> RUSSIA NATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> Political Issues </F>
<H3> <TI>   Official Explains Role </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD1001171994 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 1702 GMT 10 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD1001171994 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [By CRIME-PRESS correspondent Sergey Oleynik -- tass] </F>
  [Text] Moscow January 10 TASS -- The staff of the central 
Moscow headquarters of the Russian Counterintelligence Service 
will be reduced by more than a half and will go down from 3.500 
to 1.500 officers, first deputy director of the service Sergey 
Stepashin told a press conference on Monday. 
  Earlier spokesman of the service Aleksey Kondaurov told TASS 
that the total number of Russian counterintelligence officers 
will amount to 75.000 which is 46 per cent less than before the 
former Security Ministry was transformed into the Federal 
Counterintelligence Service. 
  Stepashin said that besides counterintelligence tasks, his 
service will, jointly with the Interior Ministry, fight 
political terrorism. 
  "The president, the government and the parliament have to 
know what's happening in the country. It is necessary to 
predict also situations connected with political terrorism, 
other actions aimed to overthrow the constitutional system", he 
said. 
  This task will be partially solved by the Interior Ministry 
and partially by the counterintelligence service, he added. 
  The main objective of the counterintelligence service, which 
directly reports to the president, is to cut short foreign 
spying and subversive activities against Russia, according to 
Stepashin. 
  The service will have a department of counterintelligence 
operations, of counterintelligence provision for strategic 
objects, of military and economic counterintelligence. 
  At the same time the former Security Ministry anti-organised 
crime department was transferred to the Interior Ministry, while 
the investigation department became a part of the office of the 
Russian prosecutor general. The former KGB investigation prison 
in Lefortovo was also trasferred to the Interior Ministry. The 
counterintelligence service, in its turn, nay get the "Alpha" 
and "Vympel" commando units. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

