<F P=100> RUSSIA NATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> Political Issues </F>
<H3> <TI>   Officials Hold News Conference </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PM1001163994 Moscow KRASNAYA ZVEZDA in Russian 11 Jan 94 p 1 </F>
<F P=103> PM1001163994 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow KRASNAYA ZVEZDA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Russian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Vasiliy Fatigarov report: "Russia's Counterintelligence -- </F>
Special Service Without Investigative Functions and Lefortovo"] 
  [Text] A press conference, timed to coincide with the 
creation of the Federal Counterintelligence Service [FCS], was 
held in Moscow yesterday. Taking part in it were Sergey 
Stepashin, first deputy director of the FCS, and Yuriy Baturin, 
assistant to the president of the Russian Federation for 
national security. 
  Henceforth the FCS, in terms of both its structure and its 
purpose, will be a special service which will in no way mirror 
the former Ministry of Security. In Sergey Stepashin's opinion, 
"all prerequisites for the revival of political surveillance 
have been destroyed." The new service is intended only to 
expose and terminate operations by foreign special services 
against the Russian Federation and "to acquire information about 
threats to our country's security." It is also tasked with 
waging a struggle against terrorism, the imports of weapons and 
drugs, and the struggle against illegal armed formations. 
Despite the fact that the Border Guard Troops have evolved into 
an autonomous service, the FCS will continue to provide 
counterintelligence backup for the effective protection of 
Russia's state borders. 
  Although the FCS is the successor of the former Ministry of 
Security, it will henceforth be subordinate only to the 
president. The service has parted with its Investigations 
Directorate, having transferred its establishment to the General 
Prosecutor's Office. And the notorious Lefortovo prison has been 
transferred to the MVD [Ministry of Internal Affairs]. 
Nonetheless, the former Ministry of Security's operational and 
technical services remain under the FCS. The question about 
transferring the "Alpha" and "Vimpel" special subunits to the 
FCS has not been raised yet. 
  According to Stepashin, the FCS's creation became necessary 
in light of the growing corruption within power structures, the 
stepped up activity of foreign special services from both nearby 
and distant foreign countries, and the attempts to recruit state 
apparatus officials. Last year alone, 20 persons were sentenced 
for espionage against Russia. 
  The press conference participants also dwelled on the 
problems of social protection for FCS military personnel. 
Former Ministry of Security staffers who have failed the 
certification process can either transfer to other state 
structures or take retirement with all statutory benefits. 
  Cutbacks in the FCS's numerical strength have affected 
primarily the central apparatus. Whereas the service as a whole 
will be 46 percent smaller than the former Russian Federation 
Ministry of Security, the center will employ only 1,500 instead 
of 3,500 staffers. Cutbacks apply primarily to backup and 
management structures, rather than to operational structures. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

